{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}
'''Richard Nugent, Lord Delvin''' (1742 – 6 August 1761) was an Irish duellist and Member of Parliament.

Nugent was the eldest son and heir of [[Thomas Nugent, 6th Earl of Westmeath]] and adopted the courtesy title of Lord Delvin in 1754 when his father acceded to the earldom.

In 1759, he was elected [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Fore (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Fore]], although he was underage. He was also commissioned a [[cornet (rank)|cornet]] in the [[1st Regiment of Dragoons]].<ref>{{cite book | title=Sketches of Old Dublin | first=A. | last=Peter | publisher=Sealy, Bryers & Walker | location=Dublin | year=1907 | pages=78–79 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gjswAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA78 | accessdate=14 December 2008}}</ref>

In July 1761, the drunken Lord Delvin accosted a female acquaintance of Capt. George Reilly, and was challenged to a duel.<ref name="gerard">{{cite book | title=Picturesque Dublin Old and New | first=Frances A. | last=Gerard | publisher=Hutchinson & Co. | year=1898 | location=London | pages=361 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HTowAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA361 | accessdate=14 December 2008}}</ref> The two crossed swords in the music room at [[Marlborough Street (Dublin)|Marlborough Bowling Green]], and Delvin was mortally wounded.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/A2A/records.aspx?cat=026-d3155_3-2&cid=-1&Gsm=2008-06-18#-1 | title=Wilmot-Horton correspondence | publisher=National Archives (UK) | accessdate=14 December 2008}}</ref> The incident led to the abandonment of Marlborough Green as a fashionable resort.<ref name="gerard" />

==Further reading==
*[https://books.google.com/books?id=cFE2AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA113 Irish Varieties] A more detailed account of the circumstances preceding the duel which ended Delvin's life.

