'''Scott N. Bradley''' (born September 13, 1951) is an American politician and university administrator from [[Utah]]. Bradley was the [[Constitution Party (United States)|Constitution Party]] nominee for [[Vice President of the United States]] in the [[United States presidential election, 2016|2016 election]], sharing the ticket with [[Darrell Castle]].<ref name="Winger">{{cite web|url=http://ballot-access.org/2016/04/16/constitution-party-nominates-darrell-castle/|title=Constitution Party Nominates Darrell Castle and Scott Bradley|last=Winger|first=Richard|date=April 16, 2016|publisher=[[Ballot Access News]]|accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref> He was also an administrator at [[Utah State University]].

Bradley ran for the United States Senate in Utah in both [[United States Senate election in Utah, 2006|2006]] and [[United States Senate election in Utah, 2010|2010]]. In 2010, he received 5.67% of the vote, which was the second highest percentage for a Constitution Party nominee for Senate against both a Democrat and Republican.<ref name="Winger"/>

==Background==
Bradley has a bachelor of arts from [[Westminster College (Utah)|Westminster College]], masters of public administration from [[Brigham Young University]] and a Ph.D. in constitutional law from [[George Wythe University]].<ref name="Davidson">{{cite news|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/700017067/Former-USU-administrator-Scott-Bradley-runs-for-Senate.html?pg=all|title=Former USU administrator Scott Bradley runs for Senate|last=Davidson|first=Lee|work=[[Deseret News]]|accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref>

