'''Taj Burrow''' (born 2 June 1978) is an Australian retired professional [[surfing|surfer]]. Taj retired from the [[ASP World Tour]] in June 2016.

==Early life==
Burrow was born in [[Yallingup]], [[Western Australia]], Australia to American parents and began surfing at age 7.<ref name=encyclopedia>{{cite book|last=Warshaw|first=Matt|title=The Encyclopedia of Surfing|year=2003|publisher=Harcourt|pages=94|url=https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=-DWQSYRx4MUC&pg=PA94&lpg=PA94&dq=burrow+surfing+hall+of+fame&source=bl&ots=UbeP5yTBDU&sig=rDX3109jfStt_A2dntGrYvlakso&hl=en&ei=LkM9TufWOILqgQfM9ID7Bw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=burrow%20surfing%20hall%20of%20fame&f=false}}</ref> At age 10, he discovered he is [[colourblind]].<ref name=Stab>{{cite web|url=http://stabmag.com/news/taj-burrow-living-high-in-the-dirty-biz-of-pro-surfing/|title=Taj Burrow – Living High In The Dirty Biz Of Pro Surfing|author=Elliot Struck|publisher=Stab Magazine|date=5 April 2013|accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref>

==Career==
In 1998 he qualified for the ASP World Tour at the age of 18 years, becoming the youngest surfer to ever win a national title.<ref name=billabong>{{cite web|title=Team - Taj Burrow|url=http://us.billabong.com/womens/team/member/taj-burrow?id=2|work=Billabong US|publisher=Billabong International Ltd|accessdate=24 September 2013|date=September 2013}}</ref> Burrow had already earned a place on the world tour a year earlier, but he turned it down stating that, as a 17-year-old, he was "too young to do the tour full-on".<ref name=encyclopedia /><ref name=surfwithtaj>[http://www.surfpix.co.nz/surf-with-taj.php]</ref> After his first year on tour in 1998, Burrow claimed the ASP World Tour Rookie of the Year award after finishing 12th place in the rankings.<ref name=fuel>[http://www.fuel.tv/shows/castmember/taj-burrow/usopenofsurfing Fuel TV Profile]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929115719/http://www.fuel.tv/shows/castmember/taj-burrow/usopenofsurfing |date=29 September 2011 }}</ref><ref name="Asp" />

In 2007 Burrow won the [[Rip Curl Pro]] at [[Bells Beach, Victoria]], Australia.<ref name=theaus>{{cite news|title=Burrow last man standing to ring bell|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/sport/burrow-last-man-standing-to-ring-bell/story-e6frg7mf-1111113332760|accessdate=24 September 2013|newspaper=The Australian|date=13 April 2007|author=Margie McDonald}}</ref> He backed this up with a victory at the 2007 Billabong Pro in [[Jeffrey's Bay]], South Africa, where he claimed the title over the then 8-time world champion, [[Kelly Slater]]. This win helped to secure his 2nd-place ranking on the [[Association of Surfing Professionals|ASP]] Men's Tour, his second runner-up season placing.

In 2009, Burrow defeated Slater in the final of the [[Billabong Pipeline Masters]] at the [[Banzai Pipeline]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Pushing our Burrow|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/pushing-our-burrow/story-e6frf9if-1225811137745|accessdate=24 September 2013|newspaper=Herald Sun|date=16 December 2009|author=AAP}}</ref> In the same year he finished fourth place on the World Tour.<ref name="Asp" />

Burrow won the 2013 Hurley Pro event in September 2013 for the first time, beating fellow Australian [[Julian Wilson (surfer)|Julian Wilson]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Taj Burrow Wins The 2013 Hurley Pro|url=http://www.surfingmagazine.com/news/taj-burrow-wins-the-2013-hurley-pro/|work=Surfing Magazine|publisher=GrindMedia, LLC|accessdate=24 September 2013|date=18 September 2013}}</ref>

===Sponsors===
As of September 2013, Burrow is sponsored by [[Globe International|Globe]], [[Billabong (clothing)|Billabong]], [[Modom Surf]], [[Von Zipper]] and Nanotune.<ref name="Asp">{{cite web|title=Surfer Profile: Taj Burrow|url=http://www.aspworldtour.com/surfers/mens-profiles/taj-burrow/|work=ASP World Tour|publisher=The Association of Surfing Professionals|accessdate=24 September 2013|date=September 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927221058/http://www.aspworldtour.com/surfers/mens-profiles/taj-burrow/|archivedate=27 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

